04935nam a22006135i 9780773596610DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a2017415379  a97807735966107 a10.1515/97807735966102doi  a(DE-B1597)654946  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA00aHD1870.P6bW24 2014 4aHD1870.P6bW24 2014 7aPOL0410002bisacsh04a338.1/810984142231 aWalsh, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTrojan-Horse Aid :bSeeds of Resistance and Resilience in the Bolivian Highlands and Beyond /cSusan Walsh. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource :b26 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustrations Follow Page -- tWhen Making Other Plans -- tIntroduction: Packets of Paradox -- tBeyond Donut-Style Research -- tEmbedded and Invented -- tDeep Connections -- tBouncing Back -- tEcological Complementarity -- tAn Interconnected Web -- tBreaking the Balance -- tFarmer Proletariat -- tHungry in Body and Spirit -- t“Dipstick”Development -- tOld Habits Die Hard -- tThe Monocropping of People, Plants, and Knowledge -- tDevelopment With Dignity -- tParadox, Resistance, and Resilience -- tAppendices -- tOverview of Field Research and Methods -- tAnalysis of Primary Research Methods -- tInterculturalism -- tChimpa Rodeo and Mojón Demographic Data -- tChimpa Rodeo and Mojón Infrastructure and Animals -- tChimpa Rodeo and Mojón Field Crops Produced -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a compelling first-hand account of development assistance gone awry, Susan Walsh recounts how national, international, and multilateral organizations failed the Jalq'a people in the Bolivian Andes during the early millennium. Intent on assisting potato farmers, development organizations pushed for changes that ultimately served their own interests, paradoxically undermining local resilience and pushing farmers off their lands. Trojan-Horse Aid challenges the idea of Western capacity-building, particularly the notion that introduced technologies related to food production are essential ingredients for sustainable livelihoods among farmers. Walsh argues that the well-intentioned organizations working in Jalq'a communities paid insufficient attention to longstanding knowledge that has supported human survival in regions where the natural world has the upper hand. Walsh goes beyond a critical review of misguided aid to offer reflections on the relationship between indigenous knowledge and resilience theory, the hopeful future of development assistance, and the contradictions in her own hybrid role as researcher and development-practitioner. In light of growing global concern over the worsening food crisis and interconnected climate extremes, Trojan-Horse Aid offers an important critique of development practices that undermine peasant strategies as well as suggestions for more effective approaches for the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAgricultural assistancezBoliviazPotosí (Department) 0aAgricultural assistancezBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aAgricultural assistancezBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aAgriculturezBoliviazPotosí (Department) 0aAgriculturezBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aAgriculturezBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aPeasantszBoliviazPotosí (Department) 0aPeasantszBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aPeasantszBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aQuechua IndiansxAgriculturezBoliviazPotosí (Department) 0aQuechua IndiansxAgriculturezBoliviazPotosí (Department). 0aQuech